            <fr:title text="baby steps in higher domain theory › what is domain theory?"><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00RN.xml" title="baby steps in higher domain theory" addr="jms-00RN" type="local">baby steps in higher domain theory</fr:link> › what is domain theory?</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Domain theory is “topology with an attitude”...</html:p>
            <beamer:pause xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" />
            <html:p>Not, to be clear, topology <html:em>qua</html:em> the study of topological spaces, but rather: <html:strong>topology <html:em>qua</html:em> the search for adequate notions of space</html:strong>.</html:p>
            <beamer:pause xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" />
            <html:p>Adequate for what? There are <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/fiore-1994.xml" title="Axiomatic domain theory in categories of partial maps" addr="fiore-1994" type="local">many</fr:link> <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/ghklms-2003.xml" title="Continuous lattices and domains" addr="ghklms-2003" type="local">viewpoints</fr:link>, and all of them are correct. But today, I speak about computer science.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
